public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        return (n >= -231) && (n <= 231 - 1) && ((n & (n - 1)) == 0);
    }
}
```

Explanation:
- We use the bitwise AND operator (`&`) to check if the difference between n and n-1 is 0. If it is, then n is a power of 3 because n = 3^x implies n-1 = 2^x or n = 2^x implies n-1 = 3^x.
- We use the range `-231` to `231 - 1` to ensure that n is an integer.

Note: This solution assumes that the input is an integer n. If the input is a string or a different data type, this solution will not work.

